  "html": "<div class=\"fr-view\"><p><strong>Adjective conjugation review</strong></p><p>There are two types of adjectives in Japanese: i-adjectives and na-adjectives. The type of adjective is determined by its ending and how you conjugate them changes on which group the adjective belongs to.&nbsp;</p><p><strong>&nbsp;い adjectives&nbsp;</strong></p><p>All i-adjectives end in い, for example, たのしい (tanoshi<strong>i</strong>):</p><table style=\"width: 83%; margin-right: calc(17%);\"><tbody><tr><td style=\"width: 20.9512%;\"><br></td><td style=\"width: 25.5784%;\">Positive</td><td style=\"width: 53.3419%;\">Negative</td></tr><tr><td style=\"width: 20.9512%;\">Non-past</td><td style=\"width: 25.5784%;\">たのしいです<br></td><td style=\"width: 53.3419%;\">たのしくないです<br></td></tr><tr><td style=\"width: 20.9512%;\">Past</td><td style=\"width: 25.5784%;\">たのしかったです<br></td><td style=\"width: 53.3419%;\">&nbsp;たのしくなかったです</td></tr></tbody></table><p>There is one exception in this group: いいです. This conjugates by changing the いい to よ</p><table style=\"width: 83%; margin-right: calc(17%);\"><tbody><tr><td style=\"width: 18.7661%; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);\"><br></td><td style=\"width: 27.7519%; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);\">Positive</td><td style=\"width: 53.3334%; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);\">Negative</td></tr><tr><td style=\"width: 18.7661%; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);\">Non-past</td><td style=\"width: 27.7519%; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);\">いいです<br></td><td style=\"width: 53.3334%; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);\">よくないです<br></td></tr><tr><td style=\"width: 18.7661%; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);\">Past</td><td style=\"width: 27.7519%; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);\">よかったです<br></td><td style=\"width: 53.3334%; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);\">よくなかったです<br></td></tr></tbody></table><p>The てform for いいです also follows the いい to よ pattern: よくて</p><p><strong>な adjectives</strong></p><p>Na-adjectives, for example, しずか:&nbsp;</p><table style=\"width: 82%; margin-right: calc(18%);\"><tbody><tr><td style=\"width: 18.9953%;\"><br></td><td style=\"width: 27.6295%;\">Positive</td><td style=\"width: 53.2182%;\">Negative</td></tr><tr><td style=\"width: 18.9953%;\">Non-past</td><td style=\"width: 27.6295%;\">しずかです<br></td><td style=\"width: 53.2182%;\">しずかじゃありません<br></td></tr><tr><td style=\"width: 18.9953%;\">Past</td><td style=\"width: 27.6295%;\">しずかでした<br></td><td style=\"width: 53.2182%;\">しずかじゃありませんでした<br></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Often people confuse na-adjectives that end with an い as an i-adjective but they are actually na-adjectives, for example きらい (kira<strong>i</strong>).</p><p><strong>Nouns</strong></p><p>The conjugation of nominal predicates or nouns used as a predicate, is the same as Na-Adjectives. For example, the noun がくせい conjugation is:</p><table style=\"width: 82%; margin-right: calc(18%);\"><tbody><tr><td style=\"width: 18.9953%;\"><br></td><td style=\"width: 27.6295%;\">Positive</td><td style=\"width: 53.2182%;\">Negative</td></tr><tr><td style=\"width: 18.9953%;\">Non-past</td><td style=\"width: 27.6295%;\">がくせいです<br></td><td style=\"width: 53.2182%;\">がくせいじゃありません<br></td></tr><tr><td style=\"width: 18.9953%;\">Past</td><td style=\"width: 27.6295%;\">がくせいでした<br></td><td style=\"width: 53.2182%;\">がくせいじゃありませんでした<br></td></tr></tbody></table></div>",
